<page_title>A reverse micelle</page_title>
<text>A reverse micelle

 
 

Lipid molecules have polar head groups with zero net charges. In a non-polar solvent (omitted in the above model for simplicity), the head groups will seek to stay together so as to minimize the electrostatic potential energy. As a result, the individual molecules (called monomers) will form an approximately spherical structure with the head groups united at the core and the tails pointing outside.

The above model uses a simplified model for the monomer, which is shown below:

  

A real lipid molecule is much more complex. For example, check out DMPG. This simulation shows that the above reverse micelle is thermodynamically stable at 300 K.

</text>
